## `<cross-cutting: event emission protocol>`
<!-- checksum: rust-fs-2b -->

### Purpose
Every mutating public method emits exactly one `Event` after its `tx.commit()` completes successfully. This section defines the contract; individual method Implementation Notes call `self.emit(...)` at the end of their `Ok` path. Emission happens on the calling thread (synchronous channel send).

### Protocol

| method       | EventKind  | node_kind              | path     | src_path    | dst_path  |
|--------------|------------|------------------------|----------|-------------|-----------|
| mkdir        | Create     | Dir                    | path     | None        | None      |
| rmdir        | Remove     | Dir                    | path     | None        | None      |
| create (new) | Create     | File                   | path     | None        | None      |
| unlink       | Remove     | (file kind)            | path     | None        | None      |
| write_fd     | Modify     | File                   | path*    | None        | None      |
| symlink      | Create     | Symlink                | path     | None        | None      |
| link         | Create     | (target kind)          | link_path| None        | None      |
| rename       | Move       | (moved kind)           | dst      | Some(src)   | Some(dst) |
| chmod        | Metadata   | (target kind)          | path     | None        | None      |
| chown        | Metadata   | (target kind)          | path     | None        | None      |
| utimes       | Metadata   | (target kind)          | path     | None        | None      |
| setxattr     | Metadata   | (target kind)          | path     | None        | None      |
| removexattr  | Metadata   | (target kind)          | path     | None        | None      |

*For `write_fd`, the path is reconstructed from the fd's inode via a reverse-lookup in `entries` (take the first entry that points at the inode; v1 compromise — ties broken arbitrarily on hard-linked files). If no entry is found (unlinked-but-still-open), the emit is skipped.

No event is fired on:
- `create` when opening an existing file (the file already existed; no new path emerged).
- `open`, `read_fd`, `close_fd` — read-only ops (`open` on its own doesn't change state; `close_fd` may cascade a delete when combined with a prior `unlink`, but the `unlink` already emitted).
- Failed mutations — events only fire after `tx.commit()?` returns `Ok`.

Readers should note: the v1 emit is unbounded (channels grow if consumers are slow); bounded queues with drop-and-report are tier-6+ work.

